    <title>Twitter is returning retweets to the way they used to be</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/c9BSyZf__oSiNxusOuAqIT-t0SA=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/68526620/acastro_170726_1777_0010.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="R0KWId"&gt;Twitter will no longer automatically show the quote tweet prompt when you try to retweet something starting on Wednesday, &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/TwitterSupport/status/1339350334162890753"&gt;the company announced&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="sZhvcw"&gt;The change to the way retweets worked was first implemented &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/10/9/21509439/twitter-election-trump-quote-tweet-labels-rules-election"&gt;in October&lt;/a&gt; ahead of the 2020 US presidential election. Twitter’s aim with the change was to encourage people to tweet and amplify information more thoughtfully.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="iCz77h"&gt;“We don’t believe that this happened, in practice,” Twitter said in &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/TwitterSupport/status/1339350334162890753"&gt;a series of tweets&lt;/a&gt;. “The use of Quote Tweets increased, but 45 percent of them included single-word affirmations and 70 percent had less than 25 characters.” Twitter also saw a 20 percent decrease in retweets and quote tweets while the automatic quote tweet prompt was in place. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="uqNu7L"&gt;
&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet"&gt;
&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr"&gt;The increase in Quote Tweets...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
