  &lt;p id="B02KAQ"&gt;Twitch will no longer allow streamers and commenters to go around calling one another “simps.” The term — a recent favorite in the Twitch community that nominally refers to men who seem desperate for a woman’s attention — will be banned when used as an insult under &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/12/9/22165342/twitch-hateful-conduct-harassment-policy-update"&gt;Twitch’s upcoming revamp of its harassment policy&lt;/a&gt;. “Incel” and “virgin” will be banned as insults, too, Twitch COO Sara Clemens said during a live-streamed town hall this afternoon. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="a18Nyy"&gt;The new policy, first spotted by esports consultant &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/Slasher/status/1339312480057782273"&gt;Rod Breslau&lt;/a&gt;, will go into effect on January 22nd. It also includes stricter rules around sexual harassment and seems to give Twitch more leeway to ban streamers and commenters who make offensive comments.&lt;/p&gt;
